  "prompt": "Are you actually supposed to break people's ribs when performing CPR?",
  "response": "Performing CPR (Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation) involves applying chest compressions to help maintain blood circulation when someone's heart has stopped. Breaking ribs is not the goal, but it can happen, especially in older adults or those with fragile bones. Here's what you need to know:\n\n1. **Why Ribs Can Break**:\n   - Chest compressions require significant force to effectively circulate blood (about 2\u20132.4 inches deep in adults).\n   - The force needed can sometimes fracture ribs or putting a strain on the sternum, especially in older individuals or those with osteoporosis.\n\n2. **Is Breaking Ribs \"Okay\"?**:\n   - While breaking ribs is not ideal, it is considered an acceptable risk when performing CPR. The priority is to save the person's life. Even if ribs are broken, CPR should continue if it is still necessary.\n\n3. **How to Minimize Risk**:\n   - Ensure proper hand placement: Place the heel of one hand on the center of the chest (lower half of the sternum) and the other hand on top.\n   - Push hard and fast (100\u2013120 compressions per minute) and allow the chest to fully recoil between compressions.\n   - Avoid leaning on the chest between compressions.\n\nIf you're trained in CPR and follow the correct technique, you reduce the risk of injury while still providing effective chest compressions. If you're untrained, hands-only CPR (without rescue breaths) is still better than doing nothing. Remember, the primary goal is to keep the person alive until professional help arrives.",
